Description: CVE-2026-50219: Prevent re-entrant calls into Expat from handlers
 The Expat parser was vulnerable to undefined behavior, use-after-free and
 heap corruption when user-defined handlers called back into Expat APIs
 (XML_Parse, XML_ParseBuffer, XML_GetBuffer, XML_ParserFree, XML_ParserReset)
 while a parse was in flight.
 .
 This patch backports upstream PR libexpat/libexpat#1246 by introducing
 handler call depth tracking. Each handler invocation is wrapped in
 beforeHandler()/afterHandler() pairs which increment and decrement a
 per-parser depth counter. The five public XML_* APIs listed above now
 reject calls when isCalledFromInsideHandler() reports a non-zero depth,
 returning XML_STATUS_ERROR / XML_FALSE / NULL as appropriate.
 .
 The upstream tree being backported is at expat 2.8.1 (commit 3fd4d1c1)
 versus the Debian bullseye expat 2.2.10 source. Only library code
 changes (expat/lib/xmlparse.c) are included; new test infrastructure
 introduced in the upstream PR (handlers.c/handlers.h, modular test
 layout) does not exist in the bullseye source tree and is therefore
 not included.
 .
 The main XML_TOK_DATA_CHARS handler path in doContent() was initially
 omitted from the backport; it is included here so that handler call
 depth tracking covers the common character-data code path (required
 for the CVE-2026-56131 regression test and for complete coverage).
Origin: backport, https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/pull/1246
Author: Sebastian Pipping <sebastian@pipping.org>
Last-Update: 2026-06-05
Bug: https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/security/advisories
Applied-Upstream: 2.8.1, https://github.com/libexpat/libexpat/commit/3fd4d1c19c30f71979b00d73d367f3d27935fad5

